|&gt;: Good News and Bad News

f() |&gt; g() just means: take the result of the call f() and pass it as the first argument to g()
Good news: this means |&gt; is intuitively ‚Äúbackwards compatible‚Äù with many base R functions
Bad news: requires checking the first argument:




getSampleSize &lt;- function() {
  return(20)
}
getSampleSize() |&gt; rbinom(10, 0.5)

 [1] 4 4 6 2 5 4 5 3 6 7 4 3 5 2 3 7 4 5 3 2




getNumTrials &lt;- function() {
  return(10)
}
getNumTrials() |&gt; rbinom(100, 0.5)

 [1] 59 45 49 54 47 55 50 53 57 50




[Quick Note:]

If you‚Äôve used R before, you may have seen the %&gt;% operator from tidyverse
‚Ä¶It got so popular that it is now built into R (as of 2023) as |&gt;!
\(\implies\) Switch from %&gt;% to |&gt; for instant efficiency boost üòé

